ANNOUNCING... THE VILLAIN VARIANT COVER!

I know it's late in the game to add something like this, but when we had the idea for the cover concept, I couldn't help myself. I hired artist Marleni Gomez to illustrate a second cover to CLONSTERS, which we are calling our VILLAIN VARIANT.

Featuring the villains of CLONSTERS -- Gogo the feral Splat, and Jekka the Splat-hunting Nugget -- there will only be 100 copies printed.

The contents of the book are the exact same, with the only difference being this cover. This is a Kickstarter exclusive collector's item! I will be selling only the standard cover at conventions, so this will be pretty much the only place to get this version of the book.

Now... there are three ways to get this:

- VILLAIN VARIANT PLEDGE: I've added this to the rewards. For $40, you will get the villain variant plus the previous rewards like the stickers, coloring book prints, and the prints.

CLONSTERS is an all-ages graphic novel about a world populated by monsters made from clay. Some are friendly like the boundlessly enthusiastic Earth Nuggets, while others like the Wild Splats live in secrecy.

Why should I back this project?

Backing this project is about each of us ensuring the U2 fan story is told.  If you are a U2 fan then you know first hand what the music has done for you, and if you can feel that, then you know what U2 has done for others too.  If you have been to a U2 show, then you have felt that common ground with thousands of others, you have felt the U2 community, joyously singing along with the band.  Expressing the connection between the fans, the music, the band and each other. 
The U2 fan community has engaged in their communities on many different levels all out of a shared value that is driven to action by the music and the bands actions.  We are a mirror of the band, and in many ways the band is a mirror of us.
By backing this project today, we join together in a community that dares to Dream Out Loud, and we affirm that the songs and experiences have meaning in our lives, and that we recognize that the story must be toldäó_ so Dream Out Loud with us today!

U2 fans, this is YOUR chance to have your stories told. There is no other fan community in existence that leans on each other, comes together, and carries each other like the U2 tribe. 
I've seen you comfort each other in times of grief, loss, and illness. I've seen you fly around the world just to see your band and be with the U2 friends who are held as close, if not closer, than your own families. I've seen you stand by the band over the years even at times when it seemed like the rest of the world was slagging them. And I've seen you form a network of solidarity and compassion which is unrivaled anywhere in the music industry.

Now I want the world to see what I've seen, and what we've all seen. You, as a community..as a family..deserve to have your unique story told and all the individual tales that make us who we are.

Filmmaker David Barry is planning to film a documentary about YOU, the fans. In order to make this happen, we need to make our goal. I've seen what you can do, and I know we can do this. If we all even chipped in $5 we would be funded in no time. Remember..there are a LOT of us.

Go to: www.dreamoutloudfilm.com and donate.

#U2Fans!  I want to hear from you today. Post your favorite photos you took of the band, and tell me the story... I'll start off with one of mine.
This was taken at the Thelonious Monk Institute of Jazz BB King Tribute show.  It was when they were rehearsing When Love Comes To Town.  Every  musician in the house came out to watch them rehearse, Jazz Legends like Wayne Shorter, Thelonious Monk Jr. Herbie Hancock... all just ringed around the stage to watch them play.  BB, Bono and Edge were having a great time, you could see they were good friends.  BB kept teasing Edge about playing cards, I guess they used to play cards on the Lovetown tour.  It was a great moment.

Now share your photos and stories!

In the past 24 hours I have heard from some amazing fans.  So many say they want to back the project, and that is encouraging... I hope they do.  
I wanted to share a couple of quick stories.  Do you guys remember the Windmill Lane watchers?  I remember hearing about them, but never met any.  It was a group of  mostly young teens that used to hang out at Windmill Lane Studios in the 1980s, they would help share what the band was up to.  And they all had some pretty incredible experiences.  Well one of them reached out to me and shared a bit of her story.  She said that the entire band would come and talk with them, but particularly Bono... he showed a lot of interest in them, and was like a big brother to them.  Thats an incredible story, what a connection, and moments like that need to be put to film, it really is almost music history they were a part of.  Please help us do that by backing the campaign. You can find it by clicking the link in my signature.

Another story... anyone remember The Bank Robbers?  They got to get up on stage with the band on the Vertigo Tour in NJ.  I was next to them talking to Bono when they gave them a CD of them doing a punk cover of Still Haven't Found What I'm Looking For.  Bono said he would listen, and he told them to stand at a specific spot on the floor, and watch for his guy.  Nobody thought he would actually do anything... but then he did.. he went and found the bank robbers and pulled them on stage and let them lead a ruff, but fun version of Still Havent Found.  I saw it all unfold, it was amazing.  Well the Bank Robbers got in touch with me yesterday too.  Another great story, and there are so many more... please help me tell them.

Exclusively for backers on Kickstarter: The very first production run features a small äóìFounders Editionäóù engraving. 

To cherish the Danish design and heritage, we named the watches after Danish Kings. As Gorm, Harald, and Svend lived before the introduction of Arabic letters in Denmark, we engraved their initials with runes at the back of the case. 

Fun Fact: If you collapse the runes for H(arald) and B(lí«tand), you see the Bluetooth logo, as the transferring technology is also named after him, apparently, symbolising his great skills in bringing people together.
